ce:section.ce:para:
The changes in the fluorescence spectrum of CTAB@NCDs were observed by adding different concentrations of Hg2+ as shown in Fig. 3
                        a, the fluorescence intensity gradually decreased with the gradual increase of Hg2+ concentration. As shown in Fig. 3b and c, the fluorescence intensity reduction efficiency (F0/F1-1) had a good linear relationship with the Hg2+ concentration in the two ranges of 150–1000 μM and 0.16–10.24 μM. The detection limit of Hg2+ was 85.71 nM when the signal ratio was 3. Compared with other fluorescent sensors based on nanomaterials (as shown in Table 1
                        ), the detection limit of this probe did have some defects, but it had the advantages of wider linear range, good selectivity, and anti-interference effect. In addition, compared with other similar methods based on carbon dots, technique preparing the CTAB@NCDs probe in this paper was simple and convenient, and the yield of the fluorescent probe was higher, which led to a wide range of applications.
